Certainly! Here's a simple example code to get you started with measuring electric field intensity using an Arduino and a capacitive sensor:

```cpp
// Libraries
#include <CapacitiveSensor.h>

// Constants
const int sensorPin = 2; // Pin connected to the capacitive sensor

// Variables
CapacitiveSensor cs_1_2 = CapacitiveSensor(1, 2); // Create a CapacitiveSensor object

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600); // Initialize Serial communication for displaying sensor readings
}

void loop() {
  long sensorValue = cs_1_2.capacitiveSensor(30); // Read the capacitive sensor value using a timeout of 30 milliseconds
  float electricFieldIntensity = map(sensorValue, 0, 1000, 0, 100); // Map the sensor value to a range (0-100) based on your calibration

  // Display the electric field intensity value
  Serial.print("Electric Field Intensity: ");
  Serial.print(electricFieldIntensity);
  Serial.println("%");

  delay(1000); // Delay for 1 second before taking the next reading
}
```

In this code, we are using the CapacitiveSensor library, which simplifies the interaction with the capacitive sensor. You will need to install this library in your Arduino IDE before uploading the code.

Make sure to connect the appropriate pin of the capacitive sensor to the designated sensorPin in the code. Also, note that you might need to adjust the map function parameters to match your specific calibration range.

Once the code is uploaded, open the Serial Monitor in your Arduino IDE (baud rate set at 9600) to see the electric field intensity measurements being displayed. Adjust the delay time in the loop() function to control the frequency of measurements.

Remember to consult the documentation and example sketches provided with your capacitive sensor and the CapacitiveSensor library for specific instructions related to your setup.
